hands_on_practices.problem:
A coherent, pseudomorphic thin film of Gallium Arsenide (GaAs) with cubic crystal symmetry is grown on a (001)-oriented substrate by Molecular Beam Epitaxy (MBE). The film is fully strained to the substrate so that the in-plane misfit strain is uniform and equal to the lattice mismatch, denoted by $f$. Let the in-plane axes be $x$ and $y$, and the surface normal be $z$. Assume the film is elastically homogeneous, the free surface satisfies a plane-stress boundary condition $\,\sigma_{z}=0\,$, and the strain is uniform through the film thickness $h$.

The generalized Hooke’s law for cubic crystals relates stress and strain by
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
\sigma_{x} \\
\sigma_{y} \\
\sigma_{z}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
C_{11}  C_{12}  C_{12} \\
C_{12}  C_{11}  C_{12} \\
C_{12}  C_{12}  C_{11}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
\varepsilon_{x} \\
\varepsilon_{y} \\
\varepsilon_{z}
\end{pmatrix},
$$
where $C_{11}$ and $C_{12}$ are the elastic stiffness constants of GaAs. Under coherent epitaxy on a (001) substrate with equal in-plane mismatch, take $\,\varepsilon_{x}=\varepsilon_{y}=f\,$ and enforce $\,\sigma_{z}=0\,$ at the free surface.

Starting from the above constitutive law and the definition of elastic strain energy density in linear elasticity, derive the appropriate in-plane biaxial modulus $M$ for this geometry and use it to compute the elastic energy per unit area $U/A$ stored in a film of thickness $h$.

Use $C_{11}=122\,\mathrm{GPa}$ and $C_{12}=57\,\mathrm{GPa}$ for GaAs, $f=0.01$, and $h=10\,\mathrm{nm}$. Express your final answer for $U/A$ in $\mathrm{J/m^{2}}$ and round your result to four significant figures. State any intermediate symbolic expressions you use, but report only the numerical value of $U/A$.
